rs/di/efg/Http/EFG/00-efg_S_index01.htm|language=sr}}\n*{{cite book|author=Popovi\u0107, Andra|year=1926|script-title=sr:\u0420\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0438 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0443\u043c : 1914-1918|work=\u0417\u0431\u0438\u0440\u043a\u0430 \u043a\u045a\u0438\u0433\u0430 \u0423\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0431\u0438\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0435 \u0443 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0443|publisher=Digital National Library of Serbia|url=http://scc.digital.bkp.nb.rs/document/UBSM-album-1914-1918|language=sr}}\n*{{cite book|author=W. H. Crawfurd Price|title=Serbia's Part in the War ...|url=https://archive.org/stream/serbiaspartinwa01pric|year=1918|publisher=Simpkin, Marshall, Hamilton, Kent & Company}} (Public Domain)\n\n{{World War I}}\n{{Bulgaria in World War I}}\n{{Wars and battles involving Serbs}}\n\n[[Category:Military operations of World War I involving Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Campaigns and theatres of World War I|Serbia]]\n[[Category:Bulgaria in World War I]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the Balkans]]\n[[Category:Serbia in World War I]]\n[[Category:Austria-Hungary\u2013Serbia relations]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "punct, other cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serbian_campaign"}
{"title_page": "French Pastry School", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = The French Pastry School\n|image           = \n|image_size      = \n|caption         = \n|motto           = \n|established     = 1995\n|type            = [[Private university|Private]]\n|endowment       = \n|faculty         = [[Jacquy Pfeiffer]] <br/><small> (Dean of Student Affairs)</small><br/> [[S\u00e9bastien Canonne]], M.O.F. <br/><small>(Dean of Faculty and Programs)</small>\n|undergrad       = \n|colors          = \n|president       = \n|city            = 226 W. Jackson Blvd. <br/> [[Chicago, IL]] 60606\n|state           = \n|country         =\n|coor            = {{coord|41.8783|-87.6349|type:edu_region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|campus          = \n|former_names    = \n|nickname        = FPS\n|affiliations    = \n|website         = {{url|http://frenchpastryschool.com}}\n}}\n\n'''The French Pastry School''' (FPS) is a vocational secondary school located in [[Chicago, Illinois]], in the United States. Its courses cover [[pastry]], [[baking]] and [[confectionery]] arts. The French Pastry School is a for-profit school,<ref name=\"bgoldberger\">Ben Goldberger, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/07/us/07cncpastry.html \u201cNew Chef Will Help Pastry Level to Rise,\u201d] ''[[New York Times]]'', February 6, 2010.</ref> and the only culinary school in the United States dedicated exclusively to teaching pastry.<ref name=\"vgerst\">Virginia Gerst, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-06-01/entertainment/0505310221_1_pastry-chef-brulee-obelisk \u201cCr\u00e8me of the crop,\u201d] ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', June 1, 2005.</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe school was founded in 1995 by master [[pastry chefs]] [[Jacquy Pfeiffer]] and [[S\u00e9bastien Canonne]], M.O.F.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/><ref>Stephen J. Serio, [http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20120413/NEWS07/120419896/the-c-suite-life-the-french-pastry-school \u201cThe C-Suite Life: The French Pastry School,\u201d] ''[[Crain's Chicago Business]]'', April 13, 2012.</ref> Pfeiffer and Canonne met in Chicago in 1992, where they discussed the lack of a serious pastry school in the US.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/> They formed the school in order to teach traditional French pastry making, based on the European master-apprentice model.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/>\n\nAt the outset, Pfeiffer and Canonne offered professional [[continuing education]] classes out of a small studio on Grand Avenue in Chicago.<ref name=\"mlittman\">Margaret Littman, [http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/19981128/ISSUE01/10001866/as-washburne-adjusts-recipe-rivals-spice-up-their-menus \u201cAs Washburne Adjusts Recipe, Rivals Spice Up Their Menus,\u201d] ''Crain's Chicago Business'', November 28, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"wrice011198\">William Rice, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-01-11/features/9801110290_1_wedding-cake-wedding-party-pastry-chef \u201cHere Comes the Cake,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', January 11, 1998.</ref> Enrollment grew, and in 1999, Mayor [[Richard M. Daley]] helped the school become affiliated with [[City Colleges of Chicago]] and the school moved into a state-of-the-art facility in the City Colleges building at 226 West Jackson Boulevard.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/><ref name=\"vgerst\"/> The affiliation with City Colleges allowed the school to provide financial aid to students.<ref name=\"athomalla\">Andie Thomalla, [http://gapersblock.com/drivethru/2010/07/09/chicagos_french_pastry_school_redefining_vocational_education/ \u201cChicago\u2019s French Pastry School: Redefining Vocational Education,\u201d] [[Gapers Block]], July 9, 2010.</ref> In 2009, they began an 11,000 square-foot renovation, adding kitchen space in the expansion.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/><ref>[http://www.foodchannel.com/articles/article/french-pastry-school-to-expand/ \u201cFrench Pastry School to Expand,\u201d] [[The Food Channel]], May 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Courses==\nThe French Pastry School offers three certificates: L'Art de la P\u00e2tisserie, a 24-week professional pastry and baking program; L'Art du G\u00e2teau, a 16-week professional cake baking and decorating program; and L'Art de la Boulangerie, a 10-week artasanal bread baking course.<ref>Barbara Revsine, [https://web.archive.org/web/20160418205535/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4426500.html \u201cCandy Kisses,\u201d] ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', February 11, 1998.</ref>\n\nL'Art de la P\u00e2tisserie was launched in 1999 and includes six months of pastry education. In the 24-week accredited program, students are taught classic French pastry methods, with subjects including baking theory and science, food sanitation, breads and breakfast pastries, cakes and tarts, and chocolate and sugar decoration.<ref name=\"wrice011198\"/><ref>Jody Robbins, \"Sweet Studies,\" ''Where Chicago'', February 2005, p. 17.</ref><ref>Elizabeth Owens-Schiele, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-08-22/features/ct-food-0822-cooking-schools-listing-20120822_1_doris-rochetti-westchester-blvd-la-buona-cucina \u201cServing up the courses,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', August 22, 2012.</ref><ref>Eloise Marie Valadez, [http://www.nwitimes.com/lifestyles/food-and-cooking/chicago-s-french-pastry-school-turning-out-talented-bakers-and/article_ac35a05b-0eda-58f5-8300-8ed7b7cdfced.html \u201cChicago\u2019s French Pastry School turning out talented bakers and confectioners,\u201d] ''[[The Times of Northwest Indiana]]'', October 19, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, L'Art du G\u00e2teau was added for students to specialize in the art of cake baking and decorating. The 16-week accredited program focuses on all aspects of creating wedding, celebration and specialty cakes. The students learn cake baking and construction, mini pastries and party favors, gumpaste and [[pastillage]], rolled [[Fondant icing|fondant]], sugar and chocolate decorating, airbrushing, mold-making methods, and cake business planning.<ref name=\"sogood\">[http://www.sogoodmagazine.com/pastry-schools/north-america/the-french-pastry-school/ \u201cThe French Pastry School,\u201d] ''So Good..'' Accessed September 20, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.foodchannel.com/articles/article/french-pastry-school-announces-two-expansions/ \u201cFrench Pastry School Announces Two Expansions,\u201d] The Food Channel, May 18, 2009.</ref>\n\nL'Art de la Boulangerie debuted in 2011, designed for students wishing to specialize in the art of bread baking. The 10-week program includes fundamentals of French breads, [[pre-ferments]], techniques and applications for levains and starters, specialty whole grains and organic breads, advanced breakfast pastries and [[viennoiseries]], and specialty breads.<ref name=\"sogood\"/><ref>[http://www.bakersjournal.com/news/french-pastry-school-offering-artisanal-bread-course-2863 \u201cFrench Pastry School offering artisanal bread course,\u201d] ''Bakers Journal'', April 8, 2011.</ref>\n\nThe school emphasizes discipline, following instructions precisely, being thorough and detail-oriented, and learning from mistakes by being persistent if a recipe does not work properly at first.<ref name=\"athomalla\"/><ref name=\"jhevredis\">Judy Hevredjs, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-12-11/features/sc-food-1206-pfeiffer-pastry-book-20131211_1_canonne-french-pastry-school-making-pastry \u201cPerfecting pastry,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', December 11, 2013.</ref> Class size is limited to 18, allowing students to work one-on-one with master pastry chefs.<ref name=\"vgerst\"/> The students are given on-going career counseling and placement assistance from the school after they graduate.<ref name=\"wrice2005\">William Rice, \"Back to School,\" ''Pastry Art & Design'', April/May 2005, pp. 48-53.</ref> The school also offers 3-to-5-day, hands-on continuing education courses to both professionals and amateurs.<ref name=\"wrice011198\"/><ref name=\"wrice2005\"/> These courses are taught year-round and on a variety of subjects. The school also invites international experts like [[Pierre Herm\u00e9]], Oriole Balaguer and Jean-Pierre Wybauw to teach special courses.<ref name=\"wrice2005\"/><ref>Louisa Chu, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-02-13/entertainment/0802110293_1_chefs-workshop-culinary \u201cHerme to teach workshop at French Pastry School,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', February 13, 2008.</ref><ref>Rick Smilow and Anne E. McBride, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=RgcK2PNxGiAC&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=the+french+pastry+school+continuing+education+article&source=bl&ots=G975aR1fdj&sig=jlUpyJCTeOvNY189DMkfIVN0mlI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_3JbVYjXJIjboASXv4OQCg&ved=0CCMQ6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=the%20french%20pastry%20school%20continuing%20education%20article&f=false Culinary Careers]'', New York: [[Clarkson Potter]], 2010, p. 44.</ref>\nas this school may be a great school it is expensive and not very many people have been to the school mostlty richer familys and fampuse pastry chefs we know today\n\n==Founders==\nAs early as 1998, the school was known for having a faculty made up of some the best pastry chefs in the world, including its founders, [[S\u00e9bastien Canonne]] and [[Jacquy Pfeiffer]].<ref name=\"mlittman\"/> Canonne is a native of France and one of a few pastry chefs in the United States to be awarded the [[Meilleur Ouvrier de France|Meilleurs Ouvriers de France]], which is the French Ministry of Labor's highest honor for craftsmen.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/> Pfeiffer was born and raised in [[Marlenheim]], a small [[Alsace|Alsatian]] village in France, to a family of bakers.<ref name=\"jhevredis\"/><ref name=\"wrice2005\"/><ref name=\"jsmarcus\">J.S. Marcus, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324445904578284004102034798 \u201cSugar, Spice and All Things Nice,\u201d] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', February 7, 2013.</ref> His pursuit of the Meilleurs Ouvriers de France commendation is the subject of the 2010 documentary ''[[Kings of Pastry]]'', directed by [[Chris Hegedus]] and [[D.A. Pennebaker]].<ref name=\"jsmarcus\"/><ref>Mike Hale, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/15/movies/15kings.html?_r=1 \u201cBehind All the Sweets There\u2019s Lots of Stress,\u201d] ''New York Times'', September 14, 2010.</ref><ref>Monica Eng, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-09-29/features/ct-food-0929-kings-of-pastry-20100929_1_sebastien-canonne-jacquy-pfeiffer-pastry-chefs \u201c\u2019Kings\u2019 of Chicago,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', September 29, 2010.</ref> Pfeiffer co-wrote the 2013 cookbook ''The Art of French Pastry'' with [[Martha Rose Shulman]],<ref name=\"jhevredis\"/><ref>Martha Rose Shulman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/dining/a-health-mavens-sweet-secret.html?pagewanted=all \u201cA Health Maven\u2019s Sweet Secret,\u201d] ''New York Times'', June 18, 2013.</ref> which won the [[James Beard Foundation Award#2014 winners|2014 James Beard Book Award for Baking and Dessert]].<ref>[http://www.jamesbeard.org/blog/2014-book-awards-recap \u201c2014 Book Awards Recap,\u201d] jamesbeard.org, May 2, 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory}}\n* [http://frenchpastryschool.com/ French Pastry School website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French Pastry School, The}}\n[[Category:Cooking schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:French pastries]]\n[[Category:For-profit universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:City Colleges of Chicago]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1995]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = The French Pastry School\n|image           = \n|image_size      = \n|caption         = \n|motto           = \n|established     = 1995\n|type            = [[Private university|Private]]\n|endowment       = \n|faculty         = [[Jacquy Pfeiffer]] <br/><small> (Dean of Student Affairs)</small><br/> [[S\u00e9bastien Canonne]], M.O.F. <br/><small>(Dean of Faculty and Programs)</small>\n|undergrad       = \n|colors          = \n|president       = \n|city            = 226 W. Jackson Blvd. <br/> [[Chicago, IL]] 60606\n|state           = \n|country         =\n|coor            = {{coord|41.8783|-87.6349|type:edu_region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|campus          = \n|former_names    = \n|nickname        = FPS\n|affiliations    = \n|website         = {{url|http://frenchpastryschool.com}}\n}}\n\n'''The French Pastry School''' (FPS) is a vocational secondary school located in [[Chicago, Illinois]], in the United States. Its courses cover [[pastry]], [[baking]] and [[confectionery]] arts. The French Pastry School is a for-profit school,<ref name=\"bgoldberger\">Ben Goldberger, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/07/us/07cncpastry.html \u201cNew Chef Will Help Pastry Level to Rise,\u201d] ''[[New York Times]]'', February 6, 2010.</ref> and the only culinary school in the United States dedicated exclusively to teaching pastry.<ref name=\"vgerst\">Virginia Gerst, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2005-06-01/entertainment/0505310221_1_pastry-chef-brulee-obelisk \u201cCr\u00e8me of the crop,\u201d] ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', June 1, 2005.</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe school was founded in 1995 by master [[pastry chefs]] [[Jacquy Pfeiffer]] and [[S\u00e9bastien Canonne]], M.O.F.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/><ref>Stephen J. Serio, [http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20120413/NEWS07/120419896/the-c-suite-life-the-french-pastry-school \u201cThe C-Suite Life: The French Pastry School,\u201d] ''[[Crain's Chicago Business]]'', April 13, 2012.</ref> Pfeiffer and Canonne met in Chicago in 1992, where they discussed the lack of a serious pastry school in the US.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/> They formed the school in order to teach traditional French pastry making, based on the European master-apprentice model.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/>\n\nAt the outset, Pfeiffer and Canonne offered professional [[continuing education]] classes out of a small studio on Grand Avenue in Chicago.<ref name=\"mlittman\">Margaret Littman, [http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/19981128/ISSUE01/10001866/as-washburne-adjusts-recipe-rivals-spice-up-their-menus \u201cAs Washburne Adjusts Recipe, Rivals Spice Up Their Menus,\u201d] ''Crain's Chicago Business'', November 28, 1998.</ref><ref name=\"wrice011198\">William Rice, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-01-11/features/9801110290_1_wedding-cake-wedding-party-pastry-chef \u201cHere Comes the Cake,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', January 11, 1998.</ref> Enrollment grew, and in 1999, Mayor [[Richard M. Daley]] helped the school become affiliated with [[City Colleges of Chicago]] and the school moved into a state-of-the-art facility in the City Colleges building at 226 West Jackson Boulevard.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/><ref name=\"vgerst\"/> The affiliation with City Colleges allowed the school to provide financial aid to students.<ref name=\"athomalla\">Andie Thomalla, [http://gapersblock.com/drivethru/2010/07/09/chicagos_french_pastry_school_redefining_vocational_education/ \u201cChicago\u2019s French Pastry School: Redefining Vocational Education,\u201d] [[Gapers Block]], July 9, 2010.</ref> In 2009, they began an 11,000 square-foot renovation, adding kitchen space in the expansion.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/><ref>[http://www.foodchannel.com/articles/article/french-pastry-school-to-expand/ \u201cFrench Pastry School to Expand,\u201d] [[The Food Channel]], May 19, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Courses==\nThe French Pastry School offers three certificates: L'Art de la P\u00e2tisserie, a 24-week professional pastry and baking program; L'Art du G\u00e2teau, a 16-week professional cake baking and decorating program; and L'Art de la Boulangerie, a 10-week artasanal bread baking course.<ref>Barbara Revsine, [https://web.archive.org/web/20160418205535/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4426500.html \u201cCandy Kisses,\u201d] ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', February 11, 1998.</ref>\n\nL'Art de la P\u00e2tisserie was launched in 1999 and includes six months of pastry education. In the 24-week accredited program, students are taught classic French pastry methods, with subjects including baking theory and science, food sanitation, breads and breakfast pastries, cakes and tarts, and chocolate and sugar decoration.<ref name=\"wrice011198\"/><ref>Jody Robbins, \"Sweet Studies,\" ''Where Chicago'', February 2005, p. 17.</ref><ref>Elizabeth Owens-Schiele, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-08-22/features/ct-food-0822-cooking-schools-listing-20120822_1_doris-rochetti-westchester-blvd-la-buona-cucina \u201cServing up the courses,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', August 22, 2012.</ref><ref>Eloise Marie Valadez, [http://www.nwitimes.com/lifestyles/food-and-cooking/chicago-s-french-pastry-school-turning-out-talented-bakers-and/article_ac35a05b-0eda-58f5-8300-8ed7b7cdfced.html \u201cChicago\u2019s French Pastry School turning out talented bakers and confectioners,\u201d] ''[[The Times of Northwest Indiana]]'', October 19, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, L'Art du G\u00e2teau was added for students to specialize in the art of cake baking and decorating. The 16-week accredited program focuses on all aspects of creating wedding, celebration and specialty cakes. The students learn cake baking and construction, mini pastries and party favors, gumpaste and [[pastillage]], rolled [[Fondant icing|fondant]], sugar and chocolate decorating, airbrushing, mold-making methods, and cake business planning.<ref name=\"sogood\">[http://www.sogoodmagazine.com/pastry-schools/north-america/the-french-pastry-school/ \u201cThe French Pastry School,\u201d] ''So Good..'' Accessed September 20, 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.foodchannel.com/articles/article/french-pastry-school-announces-two-expansions/ \u201cFrench Pastry School Announces Two Expansions,\u201d] The Food Channel, May 18, 2009.</ref>\n\nL'Art de la Boulangerie debuted in 2011, designed for students wishing to specialize in the art of bread baking. The 10-week program includes fundamentals of French breads, [[pre-ferments]], techniques and applications for levains and starters, specialty whole grains and organic breads, advanced breakfast pastries and [[viennoiseries]], and specialty breads.<ref name=\"sogood\"/><ref>[http://www.bakersjournal.com/news/french-pastry-school-offering-artisanal-bread-course-2863 \u201cFrench Pastry School offering artisanal bread course,\u201d] ''Bakers Journal'', April 8, 2011.</ref>\n\nThe school emphasizes discipline, following instructions precisely, being thorough and detail-oriented, and learning from mistakes by being persistent if a recipe does not work properly at first.<ref name=\"athomalla\"/><ref name=\"jhevredis\">Judy Hevredjs, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-12-11/features/sc-food-1206-pfeiffer-pastry-book-20131211_1_canonne-french-pastry-school-making-pastry \u201cPerfecting pastry,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', December 11, 2013.</ref> Class size is limited to 18, allowing students to work one-on-one with master pastry chefs.<ref name=\"vgerst\"/> The students are given on-going career counseling and placement assistance from the school after they graduate.<ref name=\"wrice2005\">William Rice, \"Back to School,\" ''Pastry Art & Design'', April/May 2005, pp. 48-53.</ref> The school also offers 3-to-5-day, hands-on continuing education courses to both professionals and amateurs.<ref name=\"wrice011198\"/><ref name=\"wrice2005\"/> These courses are taught year-round and on a variety of subjects. The school also invites international experts like [[Pierre Herm\u00e9]], Oriole Balaguer and Jean-Pierre Wybauw to teach special courses.<ref name=\"wrice2005\"/><ref>Louisa Chu, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-02-13/entertainment/0802110293_1_chefs-workshop-culinary \u201cHerme to teach workshop at French Pastry School,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', February 13, 2008.</ref><ref>Rick Smilow and Anne E. McBride, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=RgcK2PNxGiAC&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=the+french+pastry+school+continuing+education+article&source=bl&ots=G975aR1fdj&sig=jlUpyJCTeOvNY189DMkfIVN0mlI&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_3JbVYjXJIjboASXv4OQCg&ved=0CCMQ6AEwATge#v=onepage&q=the%20french%20pastry%20school%20continuing%20education%20article&f=false Culinary Careers]'', New York: [[Clarkson Potter]], 2010, p. 44.</ref>\n\n==Founders==\nAs early as 1998, the school was known for having a faculty made up of some the best pastry chefs in the world, including its founders, [[S\u00e9bastien Canonne]] and [[Jacquy Pfeiffer]].<ref name=\"mlittman\"/> Canonne is a native of France and one of a few pastry chefs in the United States to be awarded the [[Meilleur Ouvrier de France|Meilleurs Ouvriers de France]], which is the French Ministry of Labor's highest honor for craftsmen.<ref name=\"bgoldberger\"/> Pfeiffer was born and raised in [[Marlenheim]], a small [[Alsace|Alsatian]] village in France, to a family of bakers.<ref name=\"jhevredis\"/><ref name=\"wrice2005\"/><ref name=\"jsmarcus\">J.S. Marcus, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324445904578284004102034798 \u201cSugar, Spice and All Things Nice,\u201d] ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', February 7, 2013.</ref> His pursuit of the Meilleurs Ouvriers de France commendation is the subject of the 2010 documentary ''[[Kings of Pastry]]'', directed by [[Chris Hegedus]] and [[D.A. Pennebaker]].<ref name=\"jsmarcus\"/><ref>Mike Hale, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/15/movies/15kings.html?_r=1 \u201cBehind All the Sweets There\u2019s Lots of Stress,\u201d] ''New York Times'', September 14, 2010.</ref><ref>Monica Eng, [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-09-29/features/ct-food-0929-kings-of-pastry-20100929_1_sebastien-canonne-jacquy-pfeiffer-pastry-chefs \u201c\u2019Kings\u2019 of Chicago,\u201d] ''Chicago Tribune'', September 29, 2010.</ref> Pfeiffer co-wrote the 2013 cookbook ''The Art of French Pastry'' with [[Martha Rose Shulman]],<ref name=\"jhevredis\"/><ref>Martha Rose Shulman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/19/dining/a-health-mavens-sweet-secret.html?pagewanted=all \u201cA Health Maven\u2019s Sweet Secret,\u201d] ''New York Times'', June 18, 2013.</ref> which won the [[James Beard Foundation Award#2014 winners|2014 James Beard Book Award for Baking and Dessert]].<ref>[http://www.jamesbeard.org/blog/2014-book-awards-recap \u201c2014 Book Awards Recap,\u201d] jamesbeard.org, May 2, 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory}}\n* [http://frenchpastryschool.com/ French Pastry School website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French Pastry School, The}}\n[[Category:Cooking schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:French pastries]]\n[[Category:For-profit universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:City Colleges of Chicago]]\n[[Category:1995 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1995]]\n", "name_user": "Cra Cra catlady", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Pastry_School"}
