{"title_page": "The Child (Star Wars)", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:The Child (''Star Wars'')}}\n{{short description|Star Wars character}}\n{{Infobox character\n| image       = The Child aka Baby Yoda (Star Wars).jpg\n| name        = The Child\n| series      = [[Star Wars]]\n| first       = \"[[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\" (2019; ''[[The Mandalorian]]'') \n| creator     = [[Jon Favreau]]\n| occupation  = \n| alias       = \n| species     = [[Yoda's species]]\n| gender      = Male\n| lbl21       = Homeworld\n| data21      = Unknown\n| affiliation = \n| portrayer   = Several puppeteers\n| voice       = [[David Acord]] (with effects)\n| family = [[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|The Mandalorian]] (adoptive father)\n}}\n'''The Child''', colloquially known as \"'''Baby Yoda'''\" among fans and the media, is a [[fictional character]] from the ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[Disney+]] original [[television series]] ''[[The Mandalorian]]''. He is an [[infant]] member of the same [[Yoda's species|unnamed alien species]] as the popular ''Star Wars'' character [[Yoda]], with whom he shares a similarly strong ability with [[The Force]]. In the series, the protagonist known as \"[[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|The Mandalorian]]\" is hired to track down and capture the Child for a remnant of the fallen [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]], but instead becomes his adoptive father and protects him from the Imperials.\n\nThe Child and the Mandalorian are the only two characters who have appeared in every episode of the series. He was created by ''The Mandalorian'' creator and [[showrunner]] [[Jon Favreau]] based upon his desire to explore the mystery around Yoda and his species. The character was further developed in early conversations between Favreau and executive producer [[Dave Filoni]], and the character's imagery was defined by concept artist Christian Alzmann. The Child is mostly a work of [[animatronics]] and [[puppetry]], although accentuated with [[computer-generated imagery]].\n\nThe puppet was designed by [[Legacy Effects]] and cost about $5 million to make. It is controlled by two technicians, one who operates the eyes and mouth and another who controls other facial expressions. The character's voice and sounds were created using a combination of adult and infant vocals, as well as recordings of a [[bat-eared fox]] and [[kinkajou]].  The dynamic between the Mandalorian and the Child embody a theme of [[parenting]] and [[Father|fatherhood]] prevalent in ''The Mandalorian'', and the Child character has also raised questions about [[good and evil]] and [[nature versus nurture]] in the show.\n\nThe Child has received an overwhelmingly positive reception from fans and reviewers, is widely considered the show's [[List of breakout characters|breakout character]], and quickly became a popular [[Internet meme]]. ''[[The Guardian]]'' called him \"2019's biggest new character\",<ref name=\"Vasquez1203\" /> and ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' has claimed the character \"represents the future of Hollywood\".<ref name=\"Keegan1219\" /> Many writers have described the Child as a key part in the success of Disney+. The Child was kept secret and was deliberately withheld from ''The Mandalorian''{{'}}s prerelease marketing and merchandise plans to avoid leaks before the show aired. As a result, merchandise of the Child was not immediately available after the show debuted, which some analysts say cost Disney $2.7 million in revenue, but [[Bob Iger]], Disney's CEO at the time of ''The Mandalorian'''s premiere, has defended the strategy.\n\n==Appearances==\nThe Child is a member of the same alien species as the popular ''[[Star Wars]]'' character [[Yoda]].<ref name=\"Giardina1205\">{{cite news |last=Giardina |first=Carolyn |title=Why Jon Favreau Chose Baby Yoda: 'We Don't Know a Lot of Details About His Species' |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 5, 2019 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206084030/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/why-jon-favreau-chose-baby-yoda-we-dont-know-a-lot-details-his-species-1259164 |archive-date=December 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Alexander0105\">{{cite news |last=Alexander |first=Bryan |title=Golden Globes 2020: ''Mandalorian'' creator Jon Favreau explains why Baby Yoda is NOT Yoda |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 5, 2020 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/movies/2020/01/06/golden-globes-baby-yoda-not-yoda-says-mandalorian-jon-favreau/2821497001// |accessdate=January 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106062818/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/movies/2020/01/06/golden-globes-baby-yoda-not-yoda-says-mandalorian-jon-favreau/2821497001/ |archive-date=January 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> He is 50 years old during the events of ''[[The Mandalorian]]'', but still appears to be an [[infant]] because of the pace at which that species ages.<ref name=\"Frank1203\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Butler |first=Bethonie |title=Everything you need to know about Baby Yoda, who is probably not actually Yoda but still very cute |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 19, 2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/11/19/everything-you-need-know-about-baby-yoda-who-is-probably-not-actually-yoda-still-very-cute/ |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222144853/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/11/19/everything-you-need-know-about-baby-yoda-who-is-probably-not-actually-yoda-still-very-cute/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Joest |first=Mick |title=Let's Talk About Baby Yoda's Age In The Mandalorian |work=CinemaBlend |date=November 20, 2019 |url=https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2485314/lets-talk-about-baby-yodas-age-in-the-mandalorian |accessdate=March 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302221423/https://www.cinemablend.com/television/2485314/lets-talk-about-baby-yodas-age-in-the-mandalorian |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The species has never been given a proper name because ''Star Wars'' creator [[George Lucas]] wanted Yoda to maintain a sense of mystery.<ref name=\"Cooper1223\">{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Gael Fashingbauer |title=Baby Yoda: Everything we know about The Mandalorian star |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 23, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/baby-yoda-timeline-everything-we-know-about-the-mandalorian-breakout-star/ |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223215710/https://www.cnet.com/how-to/baby-yoda-timeline-everything-we-know-about-the-mandalorian-breakout-star/ |archive-date=December 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Vasquez1203\">{{cite news |last=Vasquez |first=Zach |title=Big deal, he is: how Baby Yoda became 2019's biggest new character |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=December 3, 2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/dec/03/baby-yoda-the-mandalorian-star-wars |accessdate=December 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209072640/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/dec/03/baby-yoda-the-mandalorian-star-wars |archive-date=December 9, 2019 |url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"Breznican1112\">{{cite news |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |title=''The Mandalorian'' Episode One: Easter Eggs and That Final Reveal, Explained |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-episode-1-easter-eggs |accessdate=February 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114155338/https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/11/the-mandalorian-episode-1-easter-eggs |archive-date=November 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of the end of Season 1 of ''The Mandalorian'', the Child has not been identified by a proper name, being referred to by other characters as \"the child\", \"the kid\", or \"the baby\".<ref name=\"Alexander0105\" /><ref name=\"Spencer1202\" /> He is the only character to appear in all eight episodes of the series other than titular [[Mandalorian]] [[bounty hunter]] character, \"[[The Mandalorian (Star Wars character)|The Mandalorian]]\" ([[Pedro Pascal]]).<ref>{{cite news |last=Liu |first=Narayan |title=Star Wars: The Mandalorian's Baby Yoda Was Nearly CGI Instead of a Puppet |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 26, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-nearly-cgi/ |accessdate=February 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127044853/https://www.cbr.com/star-wars-the-mandalorian-baby-yoda-nearly-cgi/ |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Child first appears in the series debut, \"[[Chapter 1: The Mandalorian]]\", when the Mandalorian accepts a valuable commission from a mysterious man known only as \"[[The Client (Star Wars)|The Client]]\" ([[Werner Herzog]]), who works for a remnant of the now-fallen [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Galactic Empire]]. The assignment is to track down and capture an unidentified fifty-year-old target.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smail |first=Gretchen |title=Werner Herzog's 'The Mandalorian' Character Is The Next Great 'Star Wars' Villain |work=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/werner-herzogs-the-mandalorian-character-is-the-next-great-star-wars-villain-19344045 |accessdate=January 27, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127044709/https://www.bustle.com/p/werner-herzogs-the-mandalorian-character-is-the-next-great-star-wars-villain-19344045 |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Anderton |first=Ethan |title='The Mandalorian' Footage Description: Sorry, Boba Fett, There's a New Bounty Hunter in Town |work=[[/Film]] |date=April 14, 2019 |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-footage-description/ |accessdate=January 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706021422/https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-footage-description/ |archive-date=July 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Kirby1112\">{{cite news |last=Kirby |first=Meaghan |title=''The Mandalorian'' series premiere recap: The Mandalorian embarks on a dangerous assignment |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=November 12, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/recap/the-mandalorian-series-premiere/ |accessdate=January 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211031145/https://ew.com/recap/the-mandalorian-series-premiere/ |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian and a fellow bounty hunter [[droid (Star Wars)|droid]] [[IG-11]] ([[Taika Waititi]]) infiltrate a remote and heavily-defended encampment on the planet [[Arvala-7]] and find the Child. When IG-11 attempts to kill the child, the Mandalorian protects him and instead shoots and kills IG-11<ref name=\"Kirby1112\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Hussain |first=Humza |title=The Mandalorian: Taika Waititi Wants Fans To Petition To Bring Back IG-11 |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=January 14, 2020 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-season-2-ig11-return-petition-taika-waititi/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hough |first=Q.V. |title=The Mandalorian: Who Plays IG-11 |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=January 2, 2020 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-ig11-actor-voice-taika-waititi/ |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103135412/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-ig11-actor-voice-taika-waititi/ |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In \"[[Chapter 2: The Child]]\", the Child is present when the Mandalorian is attacked by a giant [[rhinoceros]]-like creature called a Mudhorn. As the beast rushes toward the Mandalorian for the kill, the Child uses [[the Force]] to levitate the mudhorn, allowing a surprised Mandalorian to kill it.<ref name=\"Keane1115\">{{cite news |last=Keane |first=Sean |title=The Mandalorian episode 2 reveals the true nature of this Star Wars bounty |work=[[CNET]] |date=November 15, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-2-recap-the-child-disney-plus-star-wars-bounty/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126204328/https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-2-recap-the-child-disney-plus-star-wars-bounty/ |archive-date=January 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Keveney |first=Bill |title='The Mandalorian' recap: Protecting a baby Yoda isn't exactly child's play |work=[[USA Today]] |date=November 15, 2019 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/11/15/mandalorian-recap-star-wars-disney-plus-yoda-jr/4193824002/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229134720/https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2019/11/15/mandalorian-recap-star-wars-disney-plus-yoda-jr/4193824002/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kirby |first=Meaghan |title=''The Mandalorian'' recap: The Mandalorian's mission hits a snag |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=November 15, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/recap/the-mandalorian-season-1-episode-2/ |accessdate=March 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222215848/https://ew.com/recap/the-mandalorian-season-1-episode-2/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian delivers the Child to the Client on the planet [[Nevarro]] and collects his bounty in \"[[Chapter 3: The Sin]]\", after which the Client orders his colleague, [[Dr. Pershing]] ([[Omid Abtahi]]), to \"extract the necessary material\" from the Child.<ref name=\"Mitovich1122\">>{{cite news |last=Mitovich |first=Matt Webb |title=''The Mandalorian'' Reveals Client's Plan for the Child, and We Are ''Not'' Having It |work=[[TVLine]] |date=January 28, 2020 |url=https://tvline.com/2019/11/22/the-mandalorian-recap-episode-3-mando-steals-back-baby-yoda/ |accessdate=January 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126031350/https://tvline.com/2019/11/22/the-mandalorian-recap-episode-3-mando-steals-back-baby-yoda/ |archive-date=November 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Colbert |first=Stephen M. |title=The Mandalorian: What The Empire Wanted With Baby Yoda |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=November 22, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-baby-yoda-empire-scientist-clone-pershing/ |accessdate=January 28, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127041520/https://screenrant.com/star-wars-mandalorian-baby-yoda-empire-scientist-clone-pershing/ |archive-date=January 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian later has second thoughts and returns to the Imperial compound to rescue the Child, killing multiple [[Stormtrooper (Star Wars)|stormtroopers]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bundel |first=Ani |title=This 'Mandalorian' Theory About Baby Yoda Is So Important |work=[[Elite Daily]] |date=November 27, 2019 |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/this-mandalorian-theory-about-baby-yoda-is-so-important-19409245 |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222035433/https://www.elitedaily.com/p/this-mandalorian-theory-about-baby-yoda-is-so-important-19409245 |archive-date=February 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Ciacoya1113\">{{cite news |last=Ciacoya |first=Ben |title=The Mandalorian Hints at the Return of Kamino Cloning |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=November 13, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-hints-at-the-return-of-kamino-cloning/ |accessdate=February 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191218165857/https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-hints-at-the-return-of-kamino-cloning/ |archive-date=December 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> This violates the code of the Bounty Hunters' Guild, and a group of bounty hunters led by guild leader [[Greef Karga]] ([[Carl Weathers]]) ambush the Mandalorian and attempt to take the Child back from him.<ref name=\"Raymond0107\">{{cite news |last=Raymond |first=Nicholas |title=The Mandalorian: Greef Karga's Backstory Explained |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=January 7, 2020 |url=https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-show-greef-karga-carl-weathers-origin-explained/ |accessdate=January 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200108172138/https://screenrant.com/mandalorian-show-greef-karga-carl-weathers-origin-explained/ |archive-date=January 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Pham1231\">{{cite news |last=Pham |first=Danny |title=The Mandalorian: 10 Most Interesting Characters In Season 1 |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 31, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/the-mandalorian-disney-characters-best-most-interesting-season-one/ |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101130131/https://screenrant.com/the-mandalorian-disney-characters-best-most-interesting-season-one/ |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Kirby1122\">{{cite news |last=Kirby |first=Meaghan |title=''The Mandalorian'' recap: Mando makes a terrible mistake |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=November 22, 2019 |url=https://ew.com/recap/the-mandalorian-season-1-episode-3/ |accessdate=January 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211031145/https://ew.com/recap/the-mandalorian-season-1-episode-3/ |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian and the Child are saved when fellow warriors from the Mandalorian's tribe come out of hiding to defend them, allowing them to escape Nevarro.<ref name=\"Mitovich1122\" /><ref name=\"Kirby1122\" />\n\nIn \"[[Chapter 4: Sanctuary]]\", the Mandalorian seeks refuge in the sparsely populated planet [[Sorgan]]. He plans to leave the Child in a village there under the care of a widow named [[Omera]] ([[Julia Jones]]), but after another bounty hunter tracks them down, he realizes the planet is not safe.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kain |first=Erik |title='The Mandalorian' Episode 4 Recap And Review: The 'Star Wars' We Were Looking For |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/11/29/the-mandalorian-episode-4-review-this-is-the-star-wars-we-were-waiting-for/ |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126024312/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/11/29/the-mandalorian-episode-4-review-this-is-the-star-wars-we-were-waiting-for/ |archive-date=January 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Young |first=Bryan |title='The Mandalorian' Goes Full 'Seven Samurai' With \"Sanctuary\" |work=[[/Film]] |date=November 29, 2019 |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-sanctuary-review/ |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222052125/https://www.slashfilm.com/the-mandalorian-sanctuary-review/ |archive-date=December 22, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Atkin |first=Jesse |title=5 Reasons The Witcher Geralt Will Be a Better Dad Than the Mandalorian (& 5 Reasons He Won't) |work=[[Screen Rant]] |date=December 30, 2019 |url=https://screenrant.com/5-reasons-the-witcher-geralt-will-be-a-better-dad-than-the-mandalorian-5-reasons-he-wont/ |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200220043947/https://screenrant.com/5-reasons-the-witcher-geralt-will-be-a-better-dad-than-the-mandalorian-5-reasons-he-wont/ |archive-date=February 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mandalorian and the Child visit the planet [[Tatooine]] in \"[[Chapter 5: The Gunslinger]]\", during which the Mandalorian leaves the Child in the care of a mechanic named [[Peli Motto]] ([[Amy Sedaris]]). The Child and Peli are briefly abducted by a bounty hunter named [[Toro Calican]] ([[Jake Cannavale]]), whom the Mandalorian kills.<ref name=\"Keane1207\">{{cite news |last=Keane |first=Sean |title=The Mandalorian episode 5 recap: Baby Yoda travels to an iconic planet |work=[[CNET]] |date=December 7, 2019 |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-5-the-gunslinger-recap-baby-yoda-travels-to-an-iconic-planet/ |accessdate=February 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200215052741/https://www.cnet.com/news/the-mandalorian-episode-5-the-gunslinger-recap-baby-yoda-travels-to-an-iconic-planet/ |archive-date=February 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In \"[[Chapter 6: The Prisoner]]\", the Mandalorian participates in a rescue job as part of by team of mercenaries organized by [[Ranzar Malk]] ([[Mark Boone Junior]]). The Mandalorian keeps the Child hidden on his ship during the mission, but the other mercenaries eventually find him. One of them, a droid named [[Q9-0]] ([[Richard Ayoade]]), learns of the bounty on the Child and tries to kill him, but is himself destroyed by the Mandalorian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Brad |title='The Mandalorian' Episode Six Is Packed With Guest Stars And Other Delights |work=[[The Federalist (website)|The Federalist]] |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://thefederalist.com/2019/12/16/the-mandalorian-episode-six-is-packed-with-guest-stars-and-other-delights/ |accessdate=February 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213174337/https://thefederalist.com/2019/12/16/the-mandalorian-episode-six-is-packed-with-guest-stars-and-other-delights/ |archive-date=February 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Willshire |first=Edward |title=The Mandalorian Vs. Solo: Which Had the Best Criminal Crew? |work=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=December 21, 2019 |url=https://www.cbr.com/the-mandalorian-vs-solo-star-wars-criminal-crew/ |accessdate=February 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.or