              = +421-47\n| geocode                 = \n| iso_code                = \n| blank_name              = [[Slovak car registration plates|Car plate]]\n| blank_info              = LC\n<!-- website, footnotes -->\n| website                 = [https://buzitka.estranky.sk  buzitka.estranky.sk]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Buzitka''' ({{lang-hu|Bozita}}) is a village and municipality in the [[Lu\u010denec District]] in the [[Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica Region]] of [[Slovakia]].\n\n==History==\nIn [[history|historical records]], the village was first mentioned in 1350 (''Bozyta'') when it belonged to Fil'akovo. From 1554 to 1595 it was occupied by the [[Ottoman Empire]]. In 1625, when it was ruled by the family Ser\u00e9nyi, it paid tributes to Turks.\n\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Buzitka}}\n* {{Official website}}\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20071217080336/http://www.statistics.sk/mosmis/eng/run.html\n*http://www.e-obce.sk/obec/buzitka/buzitka.html\n\n{{Lucenec District}}\n\n[[Category:Villages and municipalities in Lu\u010denec District]]\n\n{{Bansk\u00e1Bystrica-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buzitka"}
{"title_page": "ATS GT", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = ATS GT\n| image = ATS GT 1X7A7944.jpg\n| caption = \n| manufacturer = [[Automobili Turismo e Sport|Automobili Turismo e Sport S.p.A]]\n| aka = \n| production = 2019 &ndash;<br>(12 units planned)\n| model_years = \n| assembly = \n| designer = \n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| platform = \n| related = [[McLaren 12C]]<br>[[McLaren 650S]]\n| engine = 3.8-litre ''[[McLaren M838T engine|M838T]]'' [[twin-turbocharged]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n| transmission = 7-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission|dual-clutch]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2670|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4700|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1960|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1210|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1300|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} (dry weight)<ref name=\"TG\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/supercars/ats-gt-700bhp-carbon-supercar-italy|title=The ATS GT is a 700bhp carbon supercar from Italy|date=1 September 2017|first=Stephen|last=Dobie|publisher=[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]|access-date= 23 October 2018}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[ATS 2500 GT]] (spiritual)\n| successor = \n| sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''ATS GT''' is a sports car manufactured by Italian automobile manufacturer [[Automobili Turismo e Sport]] (ATS). Introduced in 2017, the car pays homage to the company's first and only production model to date, the [[ATS 2500 GT]].\n\n== History and development ==\n[[File:ATS GT 1X7A7947.jpg|thumb|Rear view]]\nIn 1961, Ferrari dominated the competition in Formula One racing but few of its executives and employees were not satisfied with how the company was being run, especially the influence exerted on the company by [[Enzo Ferrari]]'s wife Laura Dominica Garello Ferrari. Ferrari did not agree with the aggrieved employees and fired them all citing that \"over evaluation of relevance to marginal facts that have nothing to do with the normal operation of a company.\" \n\nThe group of eight technicians and engineers which were laid off decided to start their own company. Thus led by [[Carlo Chiti]] and [[Giotto Bizzarrini]], they formed Automobile Turismo e Sport (ATS) and set about developing an F1 car for the 1962 season in order to stack up competition with Ferrari. But the venture was not successful. After running two cars in five races and facing retirement in majority of the races, the best result the company achieved was an 11th place. The program soon folded up in early 1963 due to repeated failures. \n\nThe company also focused on manufacturing a road car with the objective of creating a successful automobile business. In lieu of that, the ATS 2500 GT was developed and introduced at the [[Geneva Motor Show#1963|1963 Geneva Motor Show]]. Featuring a 2.5-litre V8 engine, the 2500 GT was the first mid-engine road car to reach the production stage. The 2500 GT was to be followed by a more powerful GTS variant but hard times hit the company. Due to their failure in F1, the company soon faced its demise and folded up in 1964 after having produced just 12 cars. \n\nThe ATS marque was bought by two investors in 2014 namely Emanuele Bomboi and Daniele Maritan. The newly resurrected marque set out to develop the GT, a car that captured the spirit of the original 2500 GT.<ref name=\"NA\">{{cite web|URL=https://newatlas.com/automobili-turismo-e-sport-gts/51196/|title=Stunning supercar marks the return of Automobili Turismo e Sport|date=5 September 2017|first=Scott|last=Collie|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Specifications==\n[[File:ATS GT Cockpit 1X7A7945.jpg|thumb|Interior]]\nThe front design of the car easily mimics the shape of the 2500 GT with a chin spoiler and triangular headlamps. Based on a [[McLaren 12C]]/[[McLaren 650S|650S]], the car borrows many elements from its donor car, including the airbrake, wing mirrors and dihedral doors along with mechanical components such as the engine and transmission. The rear of the car features an opaque engine cover made from carbon fibre along with rounded tail lamps and a wide mesh grille with a sweeping rear diffuser making it different than the original 2500 GT in terms of design language. An interesting design element to note is a shape running from the rear of the car and ending on the rear quarter window. The shape mimics the aerodynamic profile of the original 2500 GT. Sensors hidden in flanks of the car open the doors thus doing away with conventional door handles. \n\nErgonomics have been kept into focus on the interior. A TFT instrument cluster contains options for configuring the powertrain, suspension and aerodynamic components. The car's infotainment system makes use of Google maps. Other notable features include wireless charging and a premium Prima Orchestra hi-fi system that has 3 mm speakers at strategic points in the interior to provide good sound quality. The interior is finished in Nubuck leather and can be tailored to the customer's specifications.<ref name=\"sp1\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/100641/1-million-ats-gt-supercar-officially-launched|title=\u00a31 million ATS GT supercar officially launched|date=6 November 2017|first=Joe|last=Holding|access-date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe GT is powered by a 3.8-litre twin-turbocharged M838T V8 engine borrowed from the donor car. The engine is tuned to generate {{cvt|650|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{cvt|675|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque in standard configuration but can be further tuned to generate {{cvt|700|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{cvt|750|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque.\n\n== Performance ==\nThe GT can accelerate from {{cvt|0-97|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 3.0 seconds, {{cvt|0-194|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 9.9 seconds and can attain a theoretical top speed of {{cvt|322|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"NA\"/>\n\n== Production == \nATS has announced a production run of 12 cars. Each car will be built exactly to the customer specifications and no two cars will be similar to one another.<ref name=\"sp1\"/><ref name=\"NA\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|ATS GT (2017)}}\n\n[[Category:Cars of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2017]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:British Engine Cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = ATS GT\n| image = ATS GT 1X7A7944.jpg\n| caption = \n| manufacturer = [[Automobili Turismo e Sport|Automobili Turismo e Sport S.p.A]]\n| aka = \n| production = 2019 &ndash;<br>(12 units planned)\n| model_years = \n| assembly = \n| designer = \n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| platform = \n| related = [[McLaren 12C]]<br>[[McLaren 650S]]\n| engine = 3.8-litre ''[[McLaren M838T engine|M838T]]'' [[twin-turbocharged]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n| transmission = 7-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission|dual-clutch]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2670|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4700|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1960|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1210|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|1300|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} (dry weight)<ref name=\"TG\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/supercars/ats-gt-700bhp-carbon-supercar-italy|title=The ATS GT is a 700bhp carbon supercar from Italy|date=1 September 2017|first=Stephen|last=Dobie|publisher=[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]|access-date= 23 October 2018}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[ATS 2500 GT]] (spiritual)\n| successor = \n| sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''ATS GT''' is a sports car manufactured by Italian automobile manufacturer [[Automobili Turismo e Sport]] (ATS). Introduced in 2017, the car pays homage to the company's first and only production model to date, the [[ATS 2500 GT]].\n\n== History and development ==\n[[File:ATS GT 1X7A7947.jpg|thumb|Rear view]]\nIn 1961, Ferrari dominated the competition in Formula One racing but few of its executives and employees were not satisfied with how the company was being run, especially the influence exerted on the company by [[Enzo Ferrari]]'s wife Laura Dominica Garello Ferrari. Ferrari did not agree with the aggrieved employees and fired them all citing that \"over evaluation of relevance to marginal facts that have nothing to do with the normal operation of a company.\" \n\nThe group of eight technicians and engineers which were laid off decided to start their own company. Thus led by [[Carlo Chiti]] and [[Giotto Bizzarrini]], they formed Automobile Turismo e Sport (ATS) and set about developing an F1 car for the 1962 season in order to stack up competition with Ferrari. But the venture was not successful. After running two cars in five races and facing retirement in majority of the races, the best result the company achieved was an 11th place. The program soon folded up in early 1963 due to repeated failures. \n\nThe company also focused on manufacturing a road car with the objective of creating a successful automobile business. In lieu of that, the ATS 2500 GT was developed and introduced at the [[Geneva Motor Show#1963|1963 Geneva Motor Show]]. Featuring a 2.5-litre V8 engine, the 2500 GT was the first mid-engine road car to reach the production stage. The 2500 GT was to be followed by a more powerful GTS variant but hard times hit the company. Due to their failure in F1, the company soon faced its demise and folded up in 1964 after having produced just 12 cars. \n\nThe ATS marque was bought by two investors in 2014 namely Emanuele Bomboi and Daniele Maritan. The newly resurrected marque set out to develop the GT, a car that captured the spirit of the original 2500 GT.<ref name=\"NA\">{{cite web|URL=https://newatlas.com/automobili-turismo-e-sport-gts/51196/|title=Stunning supercar marks the return of Automobili Turismo e Sport|date=5 September 2017|first=Scott|last=Collie|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Specifications==\n[[File:ATS GT Cockpit 1X7A7945.jpg|thumb|Interior]]\nThe front design of the car easily mimics the shape of the 2500 GT with a chin spoiler and triangular headlamps. Based on a [[McLaren 12C]]/[[McLaren 650S|650S]], the car borrows many elements from its donor car, including the airbrake, wing mirrors and dihedral doors along with mechanical components such as the engine and transmission. The rear of the car features an opaque engine cover made from carbon fibre along with rounded tail lamps and a wide mesh grille with a sweeping rear diffuser making it different than the original 2500 GT in terms of design language. An interesting design element to note is a shape running from the rear of the car and ending on the rear quarter window. The shape mimics the aerodynamic profile of the original 2500 GT. Sensors hidden in flanks of the car open the doors thus doing away with conventional door handles. \n\nErgonomics have been kept into focus on the interior. A TFT instrument cluster contains options for configuring the powertrain, suspension and aerodynamic components. The car's infotainment system makes use of Google maps. Other notable features include wireless charging and a premium Prima Orchestra hi-fi system that has 3 mm speakers at strategic points in the interior to provide good sound quality. The interior is finished in Nubuck leather and can be tailored to the customer's specifications.<ref name=\"sp1\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.autoexpress.co.uk/car-news/100641/1-million-ats-gt-supercar-officially-launched|title=\u00a31 million ATS GT supercar officially launched|date=6 November 2017|first=Joe|last=Holding|access-date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe GT is powered by a 3.8-litre twin-turbocharged M838T V8 engine borrowed from the donor car. The engine is tuned to generate {{cvt|650|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{cvt|675|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque in standard configuration but can be further tuned to generate {{cvt|700|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{cvt|750|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque.\n\n== Performance ==\nThe GT can accelerate from {{cvt|0-97|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 3.0 seconds, {{cvt|0-194|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}} in 9.9 seconds and can attain a theoretical top speed of {{cvt|322|kph|mph|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"NA\"/>\n\n== Production == \nATS has announced a production run of 12 cars. Each car will be built exactly to the customer specifications and no two cars will be similar to one another.<ref name=\"sp1\"/><ref name=\"NA\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|ATS GT (2017)}}\n\n[[Category:Cars of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2017]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n", "name_user": "49.146.35.253", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ATS_GT"}
{"title_page": "The Ghost of Sierra de Cobre", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Ghost of Sierra de Cobre\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Joseph Stefano]]\n| director             = Joseph Stefano\n| starring             = [[Martin Landau]]<br>[[Judith Anderson]]<br>[[Diane Baker]]\n| music                = [[Dominic Frontiere]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = Joseph Stefano\n| executive_producer   = \n| editor               = Tony Di Marco\n| cinematography       = [[Conrad Hall]]\n| runtime              = 80 minutes\n| company              = [[CBS]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| first_aired          = 1964\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''The Ghost of Sierra de Cobre''''' is a 1964 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[thriller film]] written, produced and directed by [[Joseph Stefano]].<ref>Joseph Stefano, 84; wrote 'Psycho' script\nGayle Ronan Sims. Philadelphia Inquirer; Philadelphia, Pa. [Philadelphia, Pa]30 Aug 2006: B.9.</ref>\n\nIt was a pilot for a proposed supernatural anthology TV series for [[CBS]] called ''The Haunted''. The series was not picked up after CBS president [[James T. Aubrey]] left but some additional footage was filmed and it was released as a [[standalone film]].<ref>Stefano: Filmdom's Dr. Frankenstein\nChamplin, Charles. Los Angeles Times (1923-1995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]03 Oct 1966: C23.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Martin Landau]] as Nelson Orion\n*[[Judith Anderson]] as Paulina\n*[[Diane Baker]] as Vivia Mandore\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0312723/ ''Ghost of Sierra de Cobre''] at [[IMDb]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghost of Sierra de Cobre}}\n[[Category:1964 television films]]\n[[Category:1960s thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American television pilots]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Joseph Stefano]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dominic Frontiere]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Thriller television films]]\n[[Category:Television films as pilots]]\n[[Category:Television pilots not picked up as a series]]\n\n{{US-tv-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Ghost of Sierra de Cobre\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = \n| based_on             = \n| writer               = [[Joseph Stefano]]\n| director             = Joseph Stefano\n| starring             = [[Martin Landau]]<br>[[Judith Anderson]]<br>[[Diane Baker]]\n| music                = [[Dominic Frontiere]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = Joseph Stefano\n| executive_producer   = \n| editor               = Tony Di Marco\n| cinematography       = [[Conrad Hall]]\n| runtime              = 80 minutes\n| company              = [[CBS]]\n| distributor          = \n| budget               = \n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| first_aired          = 1964\n| last_aired           = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''The Ghost of Sierra de Cobre''''' is a 1964 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[thriller film]] written, produced and directed by [[Joseph Stefano]].<ref>Joseph Stefano, 84; wrote 'Psycho' script\nGayle Ronan Sims. Philadelphia Inquirer; Philadelphia, Pa. [Philadelphia, Pa]30 Aug 2006: B.9.</ref>\n\nIt was a pilot for a proposed supernatural anthology TV series for [[CBS]] called ''The Haunted''. The series was not picked up after CBS president [[James T. Aubrey]] left but some additional footage was filmed and it was released as a stand alone movie.<ref>Stefano: Filmdom's Dr. Frankenstein\nChamplin, Charles. Los Angeles Times (1923-1995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]03 Oct 1966: C23.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Martin Landau]] as Nelson Orion\n*[[Judith Anderson]] as Paulina\n*[[Diane Baker]] as Vivia Mandore\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0312723/ ''Ghost of Sierra de Cobre''] at [[IMDb]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghost of Sierra de Cobre}}\n[[Category:1964 television films]]\n[[Category:1960s thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American television pilots]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Joseph Stefano]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Dominic Frontiere]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Thriller television films]]\n[[Category:Television films as pilots]]\n[[Category:Television pilots not picked up as a series]]\n\n{{US-tv-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Ghost_of_Sierra_de_Cobre"}
